Note:
XML Parser - Builds AST from XML tokens

This file implements recursive descent parsing for XML 1.0/1.1, handling:
- Element trees with proper nesting
- Attributes
- Text content
- Mixed content (text and elements)
- Self-closing tags
- Comments
- CDATA sections
- Processing instructions
- Namespace-qualified names

XML AST Node Types:
- XML_DOCUMENT - Root document node
- XML_ELEMENT - Element node with name, attributes, children
- XML_TEXT - Text content node
- XML_COMMENT - Comment node
- XML_CDATA - CDATA section node
- XML_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION - Processing instruction node

Features:
- Complete XML 1.0 grammar support
- Proper nesting validation
- Attribute parsing and storage
- Mixed content support
- Error reporting with position information
- Memory-safe AST construction

Dependencies:
- xml_lexer.runa (for tokenization)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/xml/xml_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XML AST Node Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant XML_DOCUMENT as Integer is 200
Constant XML_ELEMENT as Integer is 201
Constant XML_TEXT as Integer is 202
Constant XML_COMMENT as Integer is 203
Constant XML_CDATA as Integer is 204
Constant XML_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 205

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XML AST Node Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A single node shape covers every XML kind: elements have name+attributes+children, text/CDATA/comment/PI have value, documents have children only. Distinct null slots per kind keep the schema declarative without per-kind subclasses.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Seven 8-byte fields: discriminator tag, element/PI name pointer (or 0), text/comment/CDATA/PI value pointer (or 0), attributes dictionary (or 0), children list (or 0), source line and column.
@End Implementation

Type called "XMLNode":
    node_type as Integer        Note: XML_* constant
    name as Integer             Note: Element/PI name (null for text/comment/cdata)
    value as Integer            Note: Text/comment/cdata/PI content
    attributes as Integer       Note: Dictionary of attributes (for elements)
    children as Integer         Note: List of child nodes
    line as Integer             Note: Line number in source
    column as Integer           Note: Column number in source
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: XML Parser Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The parser is a streaming cursor over the lexer; caching one current_token lets every parse_* helper peek without re-querying the lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Four 8-byte slots: lexer pointer, current_token pointer, owned error_message string (or 0), and has_error flag.
@End Implementation

Type called "XMLParser":
    lexer as Integer            Note: XML lexer
    current_token as Integer    Note: Current token
    error_message as Integer    Note: Error message (if any)
    has_error as Integer        Note: Boolean: 1 if error occurred
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Parser Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Priming the first token at construction lets every parse_* routine assume current_token is always valid (or EOF), avoiding a "have we started yet?" guard.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 32 bytes; null-check. Store lexer, null out current_token / error_message / has_error. Pull the first token from the lexer and write it into the current_token slot.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_xml_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create XML parser with lexer

    Let parser_size be 32  Note: XMLParser: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with parser_size

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize parser state
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, 0   Note: current_token = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0  Note: error_message = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 0  Note: has_error = false

    Note: Advance to first token
    Let first_token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, first_token

    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser owns its error_message buffer; destruction must release it on the standard "parse failed" path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-check the parser. Read the error_message pointer; if non-null deallocate. Deallocate the parser block.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_xml_parser" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy XML parser

    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Note: Free error message if exists
    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Management
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Token consumption happens at many call sites; isolating the cursor bump in one routine guarantees the cached current_token slot stays consistent with the lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Pull the lexer pointer from offset 0, request next_token from the lexer, store the result at offset 8, return it.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next token

    Let lexer be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 0
    Let token be proc next_token from Lexer with lexer

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, token

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Every parse decision starts with a token-type inspection; returning TOKEN_EOF for null tokens lets callers compare safely without explicit null guards.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the current_token at offset 8; if null return TOKEN_EOF. Otherwise read the type tag at the token's offset 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "peek_token_type" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current token type

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return TOKEN_EOF from Lexer
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Predicate-style lookahead lets each production decide between alternatives without copying token-shape inspection logic into every call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Call peek_token_type and return 1 if it equals expected_type, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "check_token_type" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current token matches expected type

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type from parser

    If actual_type is equal to expected_type:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A mandatory-token helper turns required-syntax checks into single-line calls and writes a uniform error message on mismatch.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Compare peek_token_type to expected_type; on mismatch call set_parse_error with the provided message and return 0. On match, advance the cursor and return 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "expect_token" takes parser as Integer, expected_type as Integer, error_msg as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Expect token of specific type, set error if mismatch

    Let actual_type be proc peek_token_type from parser

    If actual_type is not equal to expected_type:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, error_msg
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token from parser

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Error Handling
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Recording the first parse error requires copying the message into parser-owned storage so the original message buffer's lifetime is independent of the parser.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the current error_message; if non-null free it. Measure new message length, allocate length+1 bytes, copy, null-terminate. Store the pointer at offset 16 and set has_error=1 at offset 24.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_parse_error" takes parser as Integer, message as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set parser error message

    Let error_message be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16

    Note: Free previous error if exists
    If error_message is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with error_message
    End If

    Note: Copy error message
    Let msg_length be proc string_length from StringCore with message
    Let new_error be proc allocate from Layout with msg_length plus 1

    If new_error is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_copy from Layout with new_error, 0, message, 0, msg_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with new_error, msg_length, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, new_error
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 24, 1  Note: has_error = true

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Node Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Centralised node allocation initialises every slot to null/zero so consumers of partially-populated nodes (e.g. text nodes without attributes) never read uninitialised memory.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate 56 bytes; null-check. Store node_type at offset 0; zero name / value / attributes / children / line / column.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_xml_node" takes node_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create XML AST node

    Let node_size be 56  Note: XMLNode: 7 fields × 8 bytes
    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with node_size

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, 0   Note: name = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, 0  Note: value = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, 0  Note: attributes = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, 0  Note: children = null
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, 0  Note: line = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, 0  Note: column = 0

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Attribute Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML attributes are name="value" or name='value' pairs appearing inside opening tags; lifting them into a name->value Dictionary makes attribute lookup O(1) for downstream consumers and matches the XML information set representation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate an empty Dictionary. Loop while current token is TOKEN_NAME: copy the name lexeme; expect '=' then a TOKEN_STRING value; copy the string lexeme; put name->value into the Dictionary. Stop when no further name token is present.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) in attribute count, two heap allocations (name copy + value copy) per attribute.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_attributes" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse element attributes

    Let attributes be proc create from Dict

    If attributes is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Check if we have a name (attribute name)
        Let is_name be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NAME from Lexer

        If is_name is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Get attribute name
        Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
        Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

        Let attr_name be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with attr_name, 0, lexeme, 0, lexeme_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with attr_name, lexeme_length, 0

        proc advance_token from parser

        Note: Expect equals
        proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_EQUALS from Lexer, "Expected '=' after attribute name"

        Note: Expect attribute value (quoted string)
        Let is_string be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_STRING from Lexer

        If is_string is equal to 0:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected quoted attribute value"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Get attribute value
        Let value_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
        Let value_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value_token, 8
        Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with value_token, 16

        Let attr_value be proc allocate from Layout with value_length plus 1
        proc memory_copy from Layout with attr_value, 0, value_lexeme, 0, value_length
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with attr_value, value_length, 0

        proc advance_token from parser

        Note: Add to attributes dictionary
        proc put from Dict with attributes, attr_name, attr_value
    End While

    Return attributes
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Element Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
XML elements support three syntactic forms (self-closing, content, mixed content) that all start with "<NAME attr=val ...>"; the parser handles them with a single dispatcher and verifies that the closing tag name matches the opening tag to catch nesting errors.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Expect '<'. Copy the element name lexeme. Build an XML_ELEMENT node, attach name and source position. Call parse_attributes; attach result. If '/>' follows return the self-closing node. Otherwise expect '>', allocate a children list, loop calling parse_content and appending until '</' is seen; on EOF emit error. Consume '</', verify the closing name matches the opening name via strings_equal; on mismatch emit error. Expect '>'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Recursive over the document tree; each element causes one node allocation plus its attributes and child-list allocations.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Consumes untrusted XML source. Stack depth equals the source's element nesting depth - adversarial deeply-nested XML must be capped before reaching here. The closing-tag name check defends against XSS-style "</a><b>" injection by requiring the close-tag to match the open-tag exactly.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_element" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse XML element: <name attr="value">content</name> or <name />

    Note: Expect <
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_TAG_OPEN from Lexer, "Expected '<'"

    Note: Get element name
    Let is_name be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NAME from Lexer

    If is_name is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected element name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let element_name be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with element_name, 0, lexeme, 0, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with element_name, lexeme_length, 0

    proc advance_token from parser

    Note: Create element node
    Let node be proc create_xml_node from XML_ELEMENT

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, element_name
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, column

    Note: Parse attributes
    Let attributes be proc parse_attributes from parser

    If attributes is not equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, attributes
    End If

    Note: Check for self-closing tag />
    Let is_self_close be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_TAG_SELF_CLOSE from Lexer

    If is_self_close is equal to 1:
        proc advance_token from parser
        Return node  Note: Self-closing element, no children
    End If

    Note: Expect >
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE from Lexer, "Expected '>'"

    Note: Parse children (text, elements, comments, CDATA)
    Let children be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 32, children

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Note: Check for closing tag </
        Let is_close_tag be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE_OPEN from Lexer

        If is_close_tag is equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Check for EOF
        Let is_eof be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_EOF from Lexer

        If is_eof is equal to 1:
            proc set_parse_error with parser, "Unexpected EOF in element"
            Return 0
        End If

        Note: Parse child node
        Let child be proc parse_content from parser

        If child is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        proc append from List with children, child
    End While

    Note: Expect closing tag
    proc advance_token from parser  Note: consume </

    Note: Verify closing tag name matches opening tag
    Let is_closing_name be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_NAME from Lexer

    If is_closing_name is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected closing tag name"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let closing_token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let closing_lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with closing_token, 8
    Let closing_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with closing_token, 16

    Note: Compare element_name with closing tag name
    Let names_match be proc strings_equal with element_name, lexeme_length, closing_lexeme, closing_length

    If names_match is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Closing tag name does not match opening tag"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc advance_token from parser

    Note: Expect >
    proc expect_token with parser, TOKEN_TAG_CLOSE from Lexer, "Expected '>' after closing tag"

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
The closing-tag-name check needs byte-for-byte equality with a known length on both sides; an inline byte loop avoids the null-terminated string assumption that StringCore's compare would require.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
On length mismatch return 0. Otherwise loop comparing byte i of both strings; return 0 on the first mismatch, 1 if all bytes match.
@End Implementation

Process called "strings_equal" takes str1 as Integer, len1 as Integer, str2 as Integer, len2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if two strings are equal

    If len1 is not equal to len2:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be 0

    While index is less than len1:
        Let char1 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str1, index
        Let char2 be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with str2, index

        If char1 is not equal to char2:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Content Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Element content can be a mix of nested elements, text runs, comments, CDATA sections, and processing instructions; one dispatcher routed by token type keeps parse_element's loop short.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspect the current token type. TOKEN_TAG_OPEN -> parse_element; TOKEN_TEXT -> parse_text; TOKEN_COMMENT -> parse_comment; TOKEN_CDATA -> parse_cdata; TOKEN_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION -> parse_processing_instruction. Any other tag records "Unexpected token in content" and returns 0.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_content" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse content node (text, element, comment, CDATA, PI)

    Let token_type be proc peek_token_type from parser

    Note: Element
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TAG_OPEN from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_element from parser
    End If

    Note: Text content
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_TEXT from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_text from parser
    End If

    Note: Comment
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMENT from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_comment from parser
    End If

    Note: CDATA
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_CDATA from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_cdata from parser
    End If

    Note: Processing instruction
    If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION from Lexer:
        Return proc parse_processing_instruction from parser
    End If

    proc set_parse_error with parser, "Unexpected token in content"
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Text content between tags becomes XML_TEXT leaf nodes; the lexer has already resolved entity references, so the parser only copies the resolved value into a fresh buffer to decouple lifetime from the token's storage.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the text lexeme. Allocate length+1 bytes, copy, null-terminate. Build an XML_TEXT node, attach the copy at offset 16, store line/column, advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_text" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse text content node

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let text_value be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with text_value, 0, lexeme, 0, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with text_value, lexeme_length, 0

    proc advance_token from parser

    Let node be proc create_xml_node from XML_TEXT

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, text_value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, column

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Comments become XML_COMMENT leaf nodes; preserving them lets round-trip serialisers reproduce the original document, with comment-stripping callers ignoring these nodes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the comment lexeme. Allocate length+1 bytes, copy, null-terminate. Build an XML_COMMENT node, attach the copy at offset 16, store line/column, advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_comment" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse comment node

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let comment_value be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with comment_value, 0, lexeme, 0, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with comment_value, lexeme_length, 0

    proc advance_token from parser

    Let node be proc create_xml_node from XML_COMMENT

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, comment_value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, column

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
CDATA sections in XML are functionally equivalent to text but with no escaping; preserving the XML_CDATA tag (rather than collapsing to XML_TEXT) lets serialisers re-emit them in CDATA form.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the CDATA content lexeme (already de-delimited by the lexer). Allocate length+1 bytes, copy, null-terminate. Build an XML_CDATA node, attach the copy at offset 16, store line/column, advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_cdata" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse CDATA section node

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let cdata_value be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with cdata_value, 0, lexeme, 0, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with cdata_value, lexeme_length, 0

    proc advance_token from parser

    Let node be proc create_xml_node from XML_CDATA

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, cdata_value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, column

    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Processing instructions like "<?xml-stylesheet ...?>" carry document metadata that some consumers act on; preserving them as XML_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION leaves the decision to downstream code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the PI content lexeme. Allocate length+1 bytes, copy, null-terminate. Build an XML_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION node, attach the copy at offset 16, store line/column, advance.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_processing_instruction" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse processing instruction node

    Let token be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let lexeme be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let lexeme_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 32

    Let pi_value be proc allocate from Layout with lexeme_length plus 1
    proc memory_copy from Layout with pi_value, 0, lexeme, 0, lexeme_length
    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with pi_value, lexeme_length, 0

    proc advance_token from parser

    Let node be proc create_xml_node from XML_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION

    If node is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, pi_value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 40, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 48, column

    Return node
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Document Parsing
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
An XML document consists of an optional prolog (PIs and comments) followed by exactly one root element; the parser collects prolog nodes as children of a synthetic XML_DOCUMENT envelope before the root element appears.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build an XML_DOCUMENT node with an empty children list. Loop: skip top-level whitespace; on EOF break; if current token is TOKEN_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION or TOKEN_COMMENT parse and append; if TOKEN_TAG_OPEN parse_element and append (root); otherwise record an error. Return the document node.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in source token count plus the cost of recursive element parsing.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_document" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse XML document

    @Reasoning:
    An XML document consists of:
    - Optional processing instruction (<?xml version="1.0"?>)
    - Optional comments
    - Single root element
    - Optional trailing comments
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Create document node
    Let doc be proc create_xml_node from XML_DOCUMENT

    If doc is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Out of memory"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let children be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with doc, 32, children

    Note: Skip processing instructions and comments before root
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token_type be proc peek_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION from Lexer:
            Let pi be proc parse_processing_instruction from parser
            proc append from List with children, pi
        Otherwise If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMENT from Lexer:
            Let comment be proc parse_comment from parser
            proc append from List with children, comment
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Note: Parse root element
    Let is_element be proc check_token_type with parser, TOKEN_TAG_OPEN from Lexer

    If is_element is equal to 0:
        proc set_parse_error with parser, "Expected root element"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let root be proc parse_element from parser

    If root is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc append from List with children, root

    Note: Parse any trailing content (comments, PIs)
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Set token_type to proc peek_token_type from parser

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_EOF from Lexer:
            Break
        End If

        If token_type is equal to TOKEN_PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION from Lexer:
            Set pi to proc parse_processing_instruction from parser
            proc append from List with children, pi
        Otherwise If token_type is equal to TOKEN_COMMENT from Lexer:
            Set comment to proc parse_comment from parser
            proc append from List with children, comment
        Otherwise:
            Break
        End If
    End While

    Return doc
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Top-Level Parsing Entry Point
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public entry point hides the lex+parse orchestration; callers receive either the XML document node or 0 on failure.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-check source. Create the lexer; on failure return 0. Create the parser; on failure destroy the lexer and return 0. Run parse_document. Check parser.has_error; on failure clean up and return 0. Destroy parser and lexer; return the document node.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Consumes untrusted XML source. The lex+parse cleanup path always runs on every failure exit to prevent leaks.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_xml" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse XML source code to AST

    @Reasoning:
    Top-level entry point for XML parsing.
    Creates lexer and parser, parses document, handles errors.
    @End Reasoning

    If source is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create lexer
    Let lexer be proc create_xml_lexer from Lexer with source

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create parser
    Let parser be proc create_xml_parser from lexer

    If parser is equal to 0:
        proc destroy_xml_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Parse document
    Let document be proc parse_document from parser

    Note: Check for errors
    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 24

    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Let error_msg be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
        proc print with "XML parse error:", error_msg
        proc destroy_xml_parser from parser
        proc destroy_xml_lexer from Lexer with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Cleanup
    proc destroy_xml_parser from parser
    proc destroy_xml_lexer from Lexer with lexer

    Return document
End Process

Note: End of XML Parser
